{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506994"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2597"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2597"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.21,0.09,0.01,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2597"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1049"},{"type":"tags","id":"1050"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38732"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea. He has a medical history of acute myeloid leukaemia, for which he has recently completed his first course of chemotherapy. He does not take any regular medications. He denies any fever or chills.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. An electrocardiogram reveals a prolonged QTc. An electrolytes/urea/creatinine blood test is ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following electrolyte abnormalities is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypokalaemia","Hypercalcaemia","Hyponatraemia","Hypouricaemia","Hyperphosphataemia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with tumour lysis syndrome (TLS), a collection of metabolic abnormalities caused by the rapid destruction of malignant cells, typically in the setting of cytotoxic therapy. When these cells are destroyed, intracellular ions become extracellular, resulting in several electrolyte abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperphosphataemia\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the key features of TLS, along with hyperkalaemia and hyperuricaemia. The high serum phosphate levels can lead to secondary hypocalcaemia due to the formation of calcium phosphate complexes. The prolonged QTc is a key feature of hypocalcaemia, and arises due to the prolonged ST segment, which is directly proportional to the degree of hypocalcemia. It is a risk factor for proceeding to Torsades de Pointes, a life-threatening ventricular arrhythmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not consistent with the ECG changes seen in this patient. Hypokalaemia typically causes U waves and T wave flattening, which are not described here. Furthermore, hyperkalaemia would be expected in a case of TLS due to massive release of intracellular potassium during cell lysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in TLS. In fact, hypocalcaemia is more common due to the binding of calcium with excess phosphate. Hypercalcaemia would typically cause a shortened QT interval, which is not mentioned in this ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E does not cause the ECG changes described, and it is not a characteristic feature of TLS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypouricaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the opposite of what we would expect in TLS. Hyperuricaemia is a hallmark of TLS due to the breakdown of nucleic acids from rapidly lysing tumour cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with haematological malignancies, particularly those with high tumour burden like acute leukaemias, are at high risk for TLS when undergoing cytotoxic therapy. The nonspecific symptoms of nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea in this context are consistent with TLS. Management typically involves aggressive hydration, correction of electrolyte abnormalities, and measures to reduce uric acid levels, such as allopurinol or rasburicase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In tumour lysis syndrome, intracellular ions become extracellular, resulting in hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hyperuricaemia, and secondary hypocalcaemia.","ECG changes in hyperkalaemia include tall, peaked T waves, prolonged PR interval, and widened QRS complex.","Tumour lysis syndrome is more common in patients with high-grade haematological malignancies undergoing cytotoxic therapy."],"references":["Durani U, Hogan WJ. Emergencies in haematology: tumour lysis syndrome. British Journal of Haematology. 2020 Feb;188(4):494-500. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31774551/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2597"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88192"}